{"questionId":"9262","questionHtml":"<p>Hence, or otherwise, prove that the sum of the squares of any two consecutive odd&nbsp;integers is even.</p>","markschemeHtml":"<p><em><strong>METHOD 1</strong></em></p>\n<p>recognition that&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"{2n - 1}\">\n  <mrow>\n    <mn>2</mn>\n    <mi>n</mi>\n    <mo>−</mo>\n    <mn>1</mn>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span> and&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"{2n&nbsp;+ 1}\">\n  <mrow>\n    <mn>2</mn>\n    <mi>n</mi>\n    <mo>+</mo>\n    <mn>1</mn>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span>&nbsp;represent two consecutive odd&nbsp;integers (for&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"n \\in \\mathbb{Z}\">\n  <mi>n</mi>\n  <mo>∈</mo>\n  <mrow>\n    <mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Z</mi>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span>)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>R1</strong></em></p>\n<p><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"8{n^2} + 2 = 2\\left( {4{n^2} + 1} \\right)\">\n  <mn>8</mn>\n  <mrow>\n    <msup>\n      <mi>n</mi>\n      <mn>2</mn>\n    </msup>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>+</mo>\n  <mn>2</mn>\n  <mo>=</mo>\n  <mn>2</mn>\n  <mrow>\n    <mo>(</mo>\n    <mrow>\n      <mn>4</mn>\n      <mrow>\n        <msup>\n          <mi>n</mi>\n          <mn>2</mn>\n        </msup>\n      </mrow>\n      <mo>+</mo>\n      <mn>1</mn>\n    </mrow>\n    <mo>)</mo>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>valid reason <em>eg</em> divisible by 2 (2 is a factor)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>R1</strong></em></p>\n<p>so the sum of the squares of any two consecutive odd integers is even&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>AG</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>METHOD 2</strong></em></p>\n<p>recognition, <em>eg</em> that <span style=\"background-color:#ffffff;\"><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"_n\">\n  <msub>\n    <mi></mi>\n    <mi>n</mi>\n  </msub>\n</math></span></span> and&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"{n + 2}\">\n  <mrow>\n    <mi>n</mi>\n    <mo>+</mo>\n    <mn>2</mn>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span>&nbsp;represent two consecutive odd&nbsp;integers (for&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"n \\in \\mathbb{Z}\">\n  <mi>n</mi>\n  <mo>∈</mo>\n  <mrow>\n    <mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Z</mi>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span>)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>R1</strong></em></p>\n<p><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"{n^2} + {\\left( {n + 2} \\right)^2} = 2\\left( {{n^2} + 2n + 2} \\right)\">\n  <mrow>\n    <msup>\n      <mi>n</mi>\n      <mn>2</mn>\n    </msup>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>+</mo>\n  <mrow>\n    <msup>\n      <mrow>\n        <mo>(</mo>\n        <mrow>\n          <mi>n</mi>\n          <mo>+</mo>\n          <mn>2</mn>\n        </mrow>\n        <mo>)</mo>\n      </mrow>\n      <mn>2</mn>\n    </msup>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>=</mo>\n  <mn>2</mn>\n  <mrow>\n    <mo>(</mo>\n    <mrow>\n      <mrow>\n        <msup>\n          <mi>n</mi>\n          <mn>2</mn>\n        </msup>\n      </mrow>\n      <mo>+</mo>\n      <mn>2</mn>\n      <mi>n</mi>\n      <mo>+</mo>\n      <mn>2</mn>\n    </mrow>\n    <mo>)</mo>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p>valid reason&nbsp;<em>eg</em>&nbsp;divisible by 2 (2 is a factor)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>R1</strong></em></p>\n<p>so the sum of the squares of any two consecutive odd integers is even&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>AG</strong></em></p>\n<p><em><strong>[3 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"9262","referenceCode":"SPM.1.SL.TZ0.3b","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Hence, or otherwise, prove that the sum of the squares of any two consecutive odd integers is even.","paper":"1","level":"SL","questionNumber":"b","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 3]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 1—Number and algebra","Topic 1—Number and algebra","SL 1.6—Simple proof"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}